In Python it's convention to camelcase all class names. We can probably shorten this as well:

```py
class CommandLineTest(TestCase):

I think the idea here is to read the entire frame from `mTxFrameBuffer` into `mInputBuffer` and then transform it. We can simplify the whole loop with the following (read the entire frame in one go instead of byte by byte). 
```
mInputBufferLength = mTxFrameBuffer.OutFrameGetLength();
assert(mInputBufferLength <= sizeof(mInputBuffer));
mTxFrameBuffer.OutFrameRead(mInputBuffer, mInputBufferLength);
```

BTW, if you are interested, this is the little bit of magic that makes enum to string work for WPP logging (`platform/logging-windows.h`):

```
// begin_wpp config
// CUSTOM_TYPE(otError, ItemEnum(ThreadError));
// CUSTOM_TYPE(otDeviceRole, ItemEnum(otDeviceRole));
// end_wpp
```

How about something like:

```python
domains = [registered for registered in self.domains_and_ids if domain.endswith(registered)]
if len(domains) == 0:
    raise errors.PluginError(
    // ... no registered domain
    )

if len(domains) > 1:
    raise errors.PluginError(
    // ... too many registered domains ...
    )

return domains[0]
```

I can't think of a case where there _would be_ multiple matching domains, but it seems better to handle that explicitly than just pick the first we encounter.
